{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":34762,"record_hash":"sha256:bb8084ab83b31ae8148d3183e615533a9dd764d07eb8cf3dc8efd9665eefb82a","timestamp":"2026-05-11T19:59:25.416Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 5ebb11\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1077\nOutput:\n# Agentlog Sync Lifecycle\n\nThis note describes the hidden sync command:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sync\n```\n\nCapture remains a local operation. Sync is the explicit lifecycle step that uses\nGitMeta's existing remote exchange semantics to send and receive shareable\nmetadata.\n\n## Direction\n\nFor the POC, do not build agentlog-only GitMeta transport. Agentlog data is\nstored as normal shareable GitMeta metadata, so the sync command can lean on the\nexisting GitMeta lifecycle:\n\n```text\npull configured GitMeta metadata\npush local GitMeta metadata\non non-fast-forward, let GitMeta fetch/materialize/serialize and retry\n```\n\nThis means `but agentlog sync` may exchange other shareable GitMeta keys in the\nsame configured metadata remote. That is acceptable for the POC and avoids\nadding scoped refs, scoped materialization state, or custom remote selection\nbefore there is enough product pressure for it.\n\n## Goals\n\n- Reuse GitMeta's existing serialize, pull, push, materialize, and conflict\n  handling.\n- Keep `but-agentlog` free of custom Git fetch/push code.\n- Require an existing GitMeta metadata remote, configured through GitMeta's\n  normal remote setup.\n- Keep hook and capture commands local-only and fast.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- Do not sync only `gitbutler:agent-session:*` keys in this POC.\n- Do not add `--remote`; GitMeta chooses its configured metadata remote.\n- Do not infer, add, or rewrite Git remotes from `origin`.\n- Do not implement custom Git transport in `but-agentlog`.\n- Do not add conflict UI, partial push/pull modes, or background sync policy.\n\n## Command Shape\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sync\n```\n\nThe command does not need an agent argument. It operates on stored GitMeta data,\nnot on a live provider transcript.\n\nHuman output can stay terse:\n\n```text\nSynced GitMeta metadata\n```\n\nJSON output can mirror that with a simple object. More detailed counters are\nuseful later, but not required for the first lifecycle POC.\n\n## GitMet\n[TRUNCATED]\na metadata remote if one is missing.\" Those may become product\ndecisions later, but the POC stays close to GitMeta's existing behavior.\n\n## Retry Semantics\n\nKeep retries boring and bounded:\n\n```text\npull metadata from the configured GitMeta remote\npush local metadata\n\nif push is rejected as non-fast-forward:\n  ask GitMeta to resolve the push conflict\n  retry push\n```\n\nStop after a small fixed retry count and fail clearly.\n\n## Ordering And Dedupe\n\nRemote materialization can merge metadata from multiple machines. Readers should\nnot depend on stored GitMeta list order. After sync, consumers should:\n\n- dedupe transcript records by `record_hash`\n- sort by `source_key` and `record_index` within one source\n- use `timestamp`, `source_key`, `record_index`, and `record_hash` as stable\n  ordering inputs across multiple sources\n\nThis matches the data model documented in\n[GitMeta Data Model](gitmeta-data-model.md).\n\n## Privacy Posture\n\n`agentlog sync` should be explicit in the first implementation. Captured\ntranscripts are redacted, but they can still reveal sensitive project context,\nprompting strategy, file names inside tool commands, and architectural details.\n\nAvoid implying that redaction makes transcript data risk-free. Future GitButler\nUX can decide whether this same primitive runs manually, during branch/PR\npublish, or as best-effort background sync for opted-in projects.\n\n## Decided POC Choices\n\n- `but agentlog sync` is a bidirectional metadata sync command.\n- It uses GitMeta's existing configured metadata remote behavior.\n- It does not add GitMeta APIs for scoped agentlog refs.\n- It does not add a remote flag or default to `origin`.\n- It does not call custom backend ingestion or product-specific sharing logic.\n- Simplicity is preferred over early isolation; revisit scoped sync only when a\n  concrete privacy, performance, or product requirement appears.\n\nUse [Agentlog Maintainability Playbook](maintainability-playbook.md) at useful\ncheckpoints, especially if sync grows beyond this small wrapper around GitMeta.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T19:59:25.416Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}